description.$: Indhold: 1980s: Looking for the perfect beat (Sally Banes: Physical graffiti : breaking is hard to do. Steven Hager: Afrika Bambaataa's hip-hop. David Hershkovits: London rocks, Paris burns, and the B-Boys break a leg. Bill Adler: The South Bronx was getting a bad rap until a club called disco fever came along. Nelson George: Rappin' with Russell : Eddie Murphying the flak-catchers. Barry Michael Cooper: Teddy Riley's new Jack swing. John Leland: Armageddon in effect). 1990s: Pop goes the weasel (Carol Cooper: The house that rap built. Joan Morgan: The nigga ya hate to love. Scott Poulson-Bryant: The rebirth of cool. Kevin Powell: Native sons

Kierna Mayo: Caught up in the (gansta) rapture : Dr. C. Delores Tucker's crusade against "gansta rap". Dream Hampton: Hell-raiser. Carter Harris: Eazy living. Greg Tate: Diatribe. Cheo Hodari Coker: Chronicle of a death foretold. Selwyn Seyfu Hinds: Haitian homecoming / Selwyn Seyfu Hinds and Bakari Kitwana. Robert Marriott: Allah's on me. Hilton Als: No respect : a critic at large. Charles Aaron: What the white boy means when he says yo. Danyel Smith: Foxy Brown is the illest. Karen R. Good: The show, the after-party, the hotel. David Kamp: Don't hate me because I'm ghetto fabulous. Touré: The hip-hop nation : whose is it? In the end, black men must lead)

2000s: Get rich or die tryin' (Raquel Cepeda: Fool's paradise. Sacha Jenkins: The writing on the wall : graffiti culture crumbles into the violence it once escaped. Robert Christgau: Planet rock. Harry Allen: Rhythmic heart of the kings of rock : Jam Master Jay, 1965-2002. Ta-Nehisi Coates: Keepin' it unreal : selling the myth of black male violence, long past its expiration date.
